net.received.rate.maximum.kiloBitsPerSec.helpText: Maximum network data receive rate over five minute windows.

datastore.numberWriteAveraged.rate.avera.helpText: Average write IOPS sent from this VM to all of its connected datastores

datastore.totalReadLatency.absolute.aver.helpText: The average latency in milliseconds of each read operation issued by VM on its datastore.

datastore.write.rate.average.kiloBytesPe.helpText: Write Throughput of datastores connected to VM in kBps averaged over a period of 24 hour

net.broadcastByRx.ratio.compute.percent.helpText: Ratio of received broadcast packets to received packets expressed as percent.

mem.consumed.absolute.average.kiloBytes.helpText: Amount of memory consumed by a virtual machine, host, or cluster. Amount of guest physical memory consumed by the virtual machine for guest memory. Consumed memory does not include overhead memory. It includes shared memory and memory that might be reserved, but not actually used. Use this metric for charge-back purposes.   vm consumed memory = memory granted - memory saved due to memory sharing.

storage.committed.absolute.latest.bytes.helpText: Committed Space in bytes for VM storage

net.packetDropRx.ratio.compute.percent.helpText: Average ratio of dropped rx packets to total rx packets on all the virtual nics of this vms.

mem.overhead.absolute.average.kiloBytes.helpText: Amount of machine memory allocated to a virtual machine beyond its reserved amount. Amount of machine memory used by the VMkernel to run the virtual machine.

net.multicastRx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of multicast packets received during the sampling interval.

net.packetDrop.ratio.compute.percent.helpText: Average ratio of total dropped packets to total number packets on all the virtual nics of this vms.

datastore.numberReadAveraged.rate.averag.helpText: Average read IOPS sent from this VM to all of its connected datastores

datastore.totalWriteLatency.absolute.ave.helpText: The average latency of each write operation issued by this VM on its datastore.

cpu.wait.delta.summation.millisecond.helpText: CPU time spent in wait state. The wait total includes time spent the CPU Idle, CPU Swap Wait, and CPU I/O Wait states.

mem.swapinRate.rate.average.kiloBytesPer.helpText: Rate at which memory is swapped from disk into active memory during the interval. This counter applies to virtual machines and is generally more useful than the swapin counter to determine if the virtual machine is running slow due to swapping, especially when looking at real-time statistics.

net.broadcastTx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of broadcast packets transmitted during the sampling interval.

cpu.run.rate.average.percent.helpText: Percent of Time spent in Run state by all vcpus of this VM.

mem.swapped.absolute.average.kiloBytes.helpText: Current amount of guest physical memory swapped out to the virtual machine's swap file by the VMkernel. Swapped memory stays on disk until the virtual machine needs it. This statistic refers to VMkernel swapping and not to guest OS swapping.    swapped = swapin + swapout

cpu.ready_vcpu.rate.average.percent.helpText: Percentage of time per vcpu that the virtual machine was ready, but could not get scheduled to run on the physical CPU. CPU ready time is dependent on the number of virtual machines on the host and their CPU loads.

net.usage.delta.summation.kiloBytes.helpText: Network utilization (combined transmit- and receive-rates) during the interval. Sum of data transmitted and received across all virtual NIC instances connected to the virtual machine.

mem.swapoutRate.rate.average.kiloBytesPe.helpText: Rate at which memory is being swapped from active memory to disk during the current interval. This counter applies to virtual machines and is generally more useful than the swapout counter to determine if the virtual machine is running slow due to swapping, especially when looking at real-time statistics.

storage.provisioned.absolute.latest.byte.helpText: The storage capacity in bytes allocated for the VM

cpu.wait_vcpu.rate.average.percent.helpText: Percentage of CPU time per vcpu spent in wait state. The wait total includes time spent the CPU Idle, CPU Swap Wait, and CPU I/O Wait states.

net.usage.rate.maximum.kiloBitsPerSecond.helpText: Maximum total network usage rate over five minute windows.

net.packetsTx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of packets transmitted during the interval. Number of packets transmitted by each vNIC on the virtual machine.

storage.uncommitted.absolute.latest.byte.helpText: Uncommitted Space in bytes for VM storage

cpu.usagemhz.rate.average.megaHertz.helpText: CPU usage, as measured in megahertz, during the interval. Amount of actively used virtual CPU. This is the host's view of the CPU usage, not the guest operating system view.

mem.usage.absolute.average.percent.helpText: Memory usage as percentage of total configured or available memory, expressed as a hundredth of a percent (1 = 0.01%). A value between 0 and 10,000. Percentage of configured virtual machine "physical" memory:   active ÷ virtual machine configured size.

mem.active.absolute.average.kiloBytes.helpText: Amount of memory that is actively used, as estimated by VMkernel based on recently touched memory pages. Amount of guest "physical" memory actively used.

cpu.costop.delta.summation.millisecond.helpText: Time spent in co-stop state by all vcpus of this VM. Co-Stop happens if the VM has >1 vCPU, and one of them is waiting for the other. The waiting happens because ESXi does not have enough physical CPU to serve it.

net.droppedTx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of transmit packets dropped during the collection interval.

net.packetDropTx.ratio.compute.percent.helpText: Average ratio of dropped tx packets to total tx packets on all the virtual nics of this vms.

cpu.wait.rate.average.percent.helpText: Percentage of CPU time spent in wait state. The wait total includes time spent the CPU Idle, CPU Swap Wait, and CPU I/O Wait states.

net.broadcastByTx.ratio.compute.percent.helpText: Ratio of transmitted broadcast packets to transmitted packets expressed as percent.

cpu.run.delta.summation.millisecond.helpText: Time spent in Run state by all vcpus of this VM.

datastore.usage.rate.average.kiloBytesPe.helpText: The RW Throughput of datastores connected to VM in kBps averaged over a period of 24 hours

snapshot.used.absolute.latest.bytes.helpText: The size of the VM Snapshot

cpu.costop.rate.average.percent.helpText: Percentage of time spent in co-stop state by all vcpus of this VM. Co-Stop happens if the VM has >1 vCPU, and one of them is waiting for the other. The waiting happens because ESXi does not have enough physical CPU to serve it.

net.transmitted.rate.maximum.kiloBitsPer.helpText: Maximum network data transmit rate over five minute windows.

cpu.ready.delta.summation.millisecond.helpText: Absolute time that the virtual machine was ready, but could not get scheduled to run on the physical CPU. CPU ready time is dependent on the number of virtual machines on the host and their CPU loads.

net.packetsRx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of packets received during the interval. The number of packets received by each vNIC (virtual network interface controller) on the virtual machine.

net.received.rate.average.kiloBitsPerSec.helpText: Average rate at which data was received during the interval. This represents the bandwidth of the network. The rate at which data is received across the virtual machine's vNIC (virtual network interface controller).

datastore.maxTotalLatency.absolute.lates.helpText: Highest latency value across all datastores connected to VM

cpu.run_vcpu.rate.average.percent.helpText: Average Percent of Time spent in Run state per vcpu.

net.packetDrop.ratio.maximum.percent.helpText: Maximum 5 min interval ratio of total dropped packets to total number packets.

net.droppedTotal.delta.maximum.number.helpText: Maximum number of dropped packets over any 5 min interval in the selected duration (rx + tx).

net.transmitted.rate.average.kiloBitsPer.helpText: Average rate at which data was transmitted during the interval. This represents the bandwidth of the network. The rate at which data is transmitted across the virtual machine's vNIC (virtual network interface controller).

net.usage.rate.average.kiloBitsPerSecond.helpText: Network utilization (combined transmit- and receive-rates) during the interval. Sum of data transmitted and received across all virtual NIC instances connected to the virtual machine.

sys.uptime.absolute.latest.second.helpText: Total time elapsed, in seconds, since last system startup.

net.droppedRx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of receive packets dropped during the collection interval.

datastore.numberRWAveraged.rate.average..helpText: Average total IOPS sent from this VM to all of its connected datastores

cpu.usage.rate.average.percent.helpText: CPU usage as a percentage during the interval. Amount of actively used virtual CPU, as a percentage of total available CPU. This is the host's view of the CPU usage, not the guest operating system view. It is the average CPU utilization over all available virtual CPUs in the virtual machine. For example, if a virtual machine with one virtual CPU is running on a host that has four physical CPUs and the CPU usage is 100%, the virtual machine is using one physical CPU completely.   virtual CPU usage = usagemhz / (# of virtual CPUs x core frequency)

mem.vmmemctl.absolute.average.kiloBytes.helpText: Amount of memory allocated by the virtual machine memory control driver (vmmemctl), which is installed with VMware Tools. It is a VMware exclusive memory-management driver that controls ballooning. Amount of guest physical memory that is currently reclaimed from the virtual machine through ballooning. This is the amount of guest physical memory that has been allocated and pinned by the balloon driver.

datastore.read.rate.average.kiloBytesPer.helpText: Read Throughput of datastores connected to VM in kBps averaged over a period of 24 hours

cpu.ready.rate.average.percent.helpText: Percentage of time that the virtual machine was ready, but could not get scheduled to run on the physical CPU. CPU ready time is dependent on the number of virtual machines on the host and their CPU loads.

net.multicastTx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of multicast packets transmitted during the sampling interval.

net.packetsTotal.delta.summation.number.helpText: Total number of received plus transmitted packets to received packets expressed as percent.

net.broadcastRx.delta.summation.number.helpText: Number of broadcast packets received during the sampling interval.

cpu.costop_vcpu.rate.average.percent.helpText: Average Percentage of time spent in costop stage per vcpu. Co-Stop happens if the VM has >1 vCPU, and one of them is waiting for the other. The waiting happens because ESXi does not have enough physical CPU to serve it.
